{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655418"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:01:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:01:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18661"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18661"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.96,0,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11393"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80083"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11393"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18661"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65360"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7121"},{"type":"tags","id":"7126"},{"type":"tags","id":"7127"},{"type":"tags","id":"11340"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26692"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80083"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe corpus striatum is a key component of the basal ganglia, containing important nuclei involved in motor control and other functions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical structure of the corpus striatum?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surrounds the thalamus completely","Consists of caudate nucleus and putamen","Located within the cerebellar hemispheres","Forms the floor of the third ventricle","Forms part of the brainstem tegmentum"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe corpus striatum consists of the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecaudate nucleus and putamen\u003C/strong\u003E. These structures are major components of the basal ganglia and are separated by the internal capsule, they are functionally related and share similar cellular composition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurrounds the thalamus completely\u003C/strong\u003E - While the caudate nucleus has a C-shaped structure, it does not completely surround the thalamus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocated within the cerebellar hemispheres\u003C/strong\u003E - The corpus striatum is located in the cerebral hemispheres, not the cerebellum\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms the floor of the third ventricle\u003C/strong\u003E - This is formed by the hypothalamus, not the corpus striatum\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms part of the brainstem tegmentum\u003C/strong\u003E - The corpus striatum is part of the telencephalon, not the brainstem\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe putamen forms the lateral part of the lentiform nucleus, while the caudate nucleus has a characteristic C-shaped appearance as it curves around the lateral ventricle. These structures are crucial for motor control and other functions through their connections within the basal ganglia circuits.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The corpus striatum consists of the caudate nucleus and putamen, which are separated by the internal capsule.","The caudate nucleus has a C-shaped structure that curves around the lateral ventricle.","The putamen and globus pallidus together form the lentiform nucleus."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Moore KL, Dalley AF, Agur A. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Lippincott Williams and Wilkins; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65360"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18661"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65360"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-17T10:45:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-17T10:46:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11393"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80083"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"